abreast.meaning: Side-by-side. The more common "abreast of" means keeping up with, staying aware of, or remaining equal in progress with.

glower.meaning: Stare in an angry, sullen way

propriety.meaning: Conforming to good manners or appropriate behavior; justness

vernal.meaning: Relating to the spring; fresh, youthful

trifling.meaning: Trivial, not very important; so small as to be unimportant; frivolous, shallow

fledgling.meaning: A young bird that has just recently gotten its feathers, an inexperienced person (noun); new or inexperienced (adj)

impasse.meaning: Position or road from which there is no escape; deadlock

mannered.meaning: Having a particular manner, esp. an artificial one

conciliatory.meaning: Reconciling, appeasing, attempting to make the peace

stolid.meaning: Unemotional, showing little emotion, not easily moved

log.meaning: Keep a record of, write down; travel for or at a certain distance or speed (verb); a written record (noun)

grandiloquent.meaning: Relating to lofty speech, esp. to the point of being pompous, overblown, bombastic

declaim.meaning: Speak in an impassioned, pompous, or oratorical manner; give a formal speech

jettison.meaning: Discard, cast off; throw items overboard in order to lighten a ship in an emergency

hegemony.meaning: Domination, authority; influence by one country over others socially, culturally, economically, etc.

neologism.meaning: New word or phrase (or a new meaning applied to an existing word or phrase)

juncture.meaning: Critical point in time, such as a crisis or a time when a decision is necessary; a place where two things are joined together

reverent.meaning: Feeling or expressing very deep respect and awe

buttress.meaning: Support or encourage (verb); a support or prop, esp. projecting from and supporting the wall of a building (noun)

discrete.meaning: Separate, distinct, detached, existing as individual parts

indifferent.meaning: Not caring, having no interest; unbiased, impartial

clamor.meaning: Noisy uproar or protest, as from a crowd; a loud, continuous noise

whet.meaning: Stimulate, make keen or eager (esp. of an appetite)

denote.meaning: Be a name or symbol for

anoint.meaning: Rub or sprinkle oil on; make sacred, such as by a ceremony that includes applying oil to someone

searchingly.meaning: In a searching or penetrating manner; while examining closely or probing for answers

perennial.meaning: Lasting through the years or indefinitely, enduring; recurring

trite.meaning: Lacking freshness and originality, lacking effectiveness due to overuse, cliché

efficacy.meaning: The quality of being able to produce the intended effect

glib.meaning: Fluent and easy in a way that suggests superficiality or insincerity

sap.meaning: The inner fluid of a plant or any essential body fluid; energy, vitality; a person taken advantage of (noun); undermine, weaken, tire out (verb)

dyspeptic.meaning: Grumpy, pessimistic, irritable; suffering from dyspepsia (indigestion)

sporadic.meaning: Occasional, happening irregularly or in scattered locations

lament.meaning: Mourn; express grief, sorrow, or regret (verb); an expression of grief, esp. as a song or poem (noun)

futile.meaning: Producing no useful result, ineffective; trivial or unimportant

aerie.meaning: Dwelling or fortress built on a high place; the nest of a bird of prey, such as an eagle or hawk, built on a mountain or cliff

terrestrial.meaning: Relating to the Earth or to land; worldly

lumber.meaning: Walk in a heavy or clumsy way, sometimes due to being weighed down

recalcitrant.meaning: Not obedient, resisting authority, hard to manage

quixotic.meaning: Extremely impractical but very romantic, chivalrous, or idealistic; impulsive

incorporate.meaning: Combine, unite; form a legal corporation; embody, give physical form to

gauche.meaning: Tactless, lacking social grace, awkward, crude

dissemble.meaning: Mislead, conceal the truth, put on a false appearance of

inordinate.meaning: Excessive, not within proper limits, unrestrained

primacy.meaning: The state of being first or most important

sybarite.meaning: Person devoted to pleasure and luxury

scathing.meaning: Severe, injurious; bitterly harsh or critical (as a remark)

euphony.meaning: Pleasing or sweet sound, especially as formed by a harmonious use of words

fervid.meaning: Very hot; heated in passion or enthusiasm

opaque.meaning: Not translucent; not allowing light, heat, etc. to pass through; dark, dull, unclear or stupid

egress.meaning: An exit or the action of exiting

licentious.meaning: Sexually unrestrained; immoral; ignoring the rules

artifact.meaning: Any object made by humans, especially those from an earlier time, such as those excavated by archaeologists

facetious.meaning: Joking, humorous, esp. inappropriately; not serious, concerned with frivolous things

rue.meaning: Regret, remorse (noun); to feel regret or remorse (verb)

reproach.meaning: Blame, disgrace (noun); criticize, express disappointment in (verb)

analgesia.meaning: Pain relief; inability to feel pain

plausible.meaning: Believable; having the appearance of truth

caustic.meaning: Capable of corroding metal or burning the skin; very critical or sarcastic
